    lng: -1.5459,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "St Mary the Virgin, Bampton, is built on the site of an Anglo-Saxon royal minster dating from around 950 AD. The herringbone masonry visible in the central crossing tower is surviving Saxon stonework — look for the diagonal brick pattern, distinct from later Norman work. Find the gabled recess in the north transept: this is thought to be the physical remnant of the shrine of St Beornwald, a local saint whose cult survived from 950 AD until the Reformation. An early 12th-century charter requires the chaplain of Alvescot to attend St Beornwald's feast here — the cult was active for 600 years. Inside are medieval effigies, monumental brasses, a 1250 stone figure of John the Baptist (rescued from a storm in 1991), and a stone knight said to be Sir Gilbert Talbot (d.1419). This doubles as the Downton Abbey village church — all six seasons and both films were shot here.",
