    lng: -1.5100,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Start at Tadpole Bridge (park by The Trout Inn — note the sign: 'The Trout, Kept by A. Herring', an old landlord with a fisherman's surname who accidentally created the most celebrated piece of river wit on the upper Thames). Walk the Thames Path north-east for 4 miles to Shifford Lock. The path is entirely road-free: meadows, cows, herons, occasional kingfisher. In winter the meadows flood dramatically — sometimes knee-deep — and the same path becomes a wellies-essential inland sea. In summer it is quiet, warm, and wildflowered. Shifford Lock has an unusually remote café in the lock-keeper's cottage (check ahead). Return via footpath inland for a 7-mile loop. Or drive one car to each end.",
