    description: "St Michael and All Angels, Eaton Hastings, is accessible only by footpath along the Thames bank — there is no road. The village it served was depopulated after 1349 (plague, emparking, wool conversion), leaving the 11th-century church standing alone in a Thames meadow. Its west window contains glass designed by William Morris and Ford Madox Brown in 1860, made by Morris & Co. — archangels Michael, Raphael, and Gabriel in rich Pre-Raphaelite colour. A second window is by Burne-Jones. Best approach: park at Buscot, walk the Thames Path east for 1.5 miles. The church is almost always open (key with local farmer if locked; try the door first). In late afternoon, the west window is lit from behind and the colour fills the tiny space.",
