    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Duxford Ford — 'Dudochesforde' in the Domesday Book (1086) — is the only surviving, usable ford along the entire navigable River Thames. Every other crossing is a bridge or a lock. The ford has a concrete floor added in the 20th century and leads to a footbridge island giving pedestrian access to Chimney on the north bank. Approach via a bridleway from the lane east of Duxford hamlet. The walk through flat Thames meadow is remote and quiet. In summer, it is possible to paddle or wade the ford (shallow in dry conditions). In winter it floods to knee depth. Combine with Chimney village (population ~28, no shop, no church, no pub, named from the Saxon Ceomann's Island) via the footbridge and walk the Chimney Meadows wildflower reserve.",
