    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "St Mary the Virgin at Black Bourton has the most extensive medieval wall paintings in the immediate area — 13th-century work covering both nave walls in large scenes of red and orange ochre. North wall: Tree of Jesse, St Christopher, the martyrdom of Thomas Becket, Coronation of the Virgin, Baptism of Jesus, Saints Peter and Paul, and the Stoning of St Stephen. South wall: St Richard, Adoration of the Magi, Massacre of the Innocents, Angel to St Joseph. The paintings were whitewashed after the Reformation (standard practice), rediscovered by Canon Lupton in 1866, then re-covered again without his permission, and finally rediscovered a second time by the art historian E.W. Tristram in 1932. Open daily 9:30am–5pm, no key needed. Phone 01993 606350. Parking on the Burford Road verge.",
