    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Coleshill House was the top-secret national headquarters of the Auxiliary Units from 1940 to 1944 — Britain's stay-behind resistance, trained to assassinate, demolish and sabotage behind German lines if invasion succeeded. Around 3,500 farmers, gamekeepers and poachers came here in total secrecy for weekend training. Each patrol expected to survive about two weeks after activation before being killed. The house burned down in 1952, but the National Trust now runs 'Secrets of Coleshill' guided tours of the surviving wartime infrastructure including a replica Operational Base (underground bunker). Separate oddity: Katherine Pleydell-Bouverie set up her 'Cole Pottery' here in 1925 with a two-chambered wood-fired kiln built by a Japanese kiln-maker, Tsurunosuke Matsubayashi — it consumed 2 tonnes of timber per 36-hour firing. The model farm and estate are free to walk; NT tours have a charge.",
