    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "The medieval kitchen at Stanton Harcourt Manor (open on specific days in summer — check stanton-harcourt.co.uk) is the most complete surviving separate kitchen building in England. Grade I listed. Three medieval ovens; original fire spits; an octagonal pointed roof topped with a lead griffin with no chimney — smoke rose to ceiling holes. In 1717–18 Alexander Pope stayed in the adjacent tower room while translating books 5–8 of Homer's Iliad. He compared the kitchen to Vulcan's forge in his letters. The manor church of St Michael has extraordinary Harcourt monuments — a 14th-century chantry chapel with painted medieval tombs including one where two knights share a single stone slab. Find the medieval fish ponds in the field behind the church (rectangular depressions, still clearly visible). Stanton Harcourt is 3 miles from Buckland.",
