    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Kelmscott Manor (open Thu/Fri/Sat, April–October; book tickets at kelmscottmanor.org.uk) is the country retreat William Morris leased from 1871 until his death in 1896. The specific story: Morris and Dante Gabriel Rossetti jointly took the lease in 1871, then Morris immediately went to Iceland for the summer, leaving Rossetti and Morris's wife Jane alone at the manor. Rossetti had been obsessively painting Jane for years. They punted on the Thames; Rossetti wrote poetry and made more pictures of Jane. This arrangement continued for several summers. The manor looks exactly as it did in the 1890s — May Morris, William's daughter, stipulated in her bequest that nothing be modernised. Original wallpaper, original printing blocks, the mulberry tree Morris found already ancient when he arrived. Morris is buried in the village churchyard under a headstone he designed himself in a Viking grave marker style.",
