    description: "Witney was the blanket capital of England for 400 years. The Blanket Hall (1721) on the High Street is where every blanket made in town came for weighing and measuring — 150 looms by 1677, 3,000 people in related trades. Queen Anne's 1711 charter gave the Company of Blanket Weavers jurisdiction over all blanket production within a 20-mile radius. Blanket Row (a terrace of houses, now ordinary) is where blankets were stretched on timber racks called 'tenters' to dry — the hooks that held them gave English the phrase 'on tenterhooks.' The mill water leat (channel) still runs through town. The old Early's Mill building is now a Waitrose, but the mill pond and millrace are still visible. A 45-minute walking circuit covers all the industrial history. Combine with Cogges Manor Farm Museum (working Victorian farm with live animals) a 10-minute walk away.",
