    lng: -1.5350,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Rushey Lock (built 1790, rebuilt 1898) is one of the last manually operated pound locks on the Thames — the paddles and sluice gates are wound entirely by hand using a windlass. Watch a boat go through: the lock-keeper walks the beam to close the near gate, uses a boat-hook pole to control the off-side, and winds the gear by hand throughout. The lock-keeper's cottage has a topiary in the garden — specifically a frog-shaped bush, the lock-keeper's personal touch. A 1909 Thames account describes a lock-keeper here chatting about 'the extortions of river inns, his son's trophies from South Africa, local drownings, his eel-traps, the winter floods, and his own small commerce in rushes.' The atmosphere has not substantially changed. Walk from Tadpole Bridge (1 mile upstream) via the Thames Path, south bank.",
