    description: "St Faith's, Shellingford (2 miles from Buckland) rewards 15 minutes of close attention. The south door has Norman moulding that terminates in carved serpent heads. Inside the vestry (formerly the north door), find beak-head carvings — the Norman motif of beast heads biting a roll moulding — a survival from the 12th century. The east window has fragments of 14th and 15th-century glass gathered from all around the church during Victorian restoration. Among the monuments: a piece by John Flaxman (who made the Nelson monument in St Paul's) to William, 2nd Viscount Ashbrook (1767–1802). The spire was destroyed by lightning in 1848 and the rebuilt version (1852) sits oddly on the 13th-century tower. The whole church is a palimpsest of accidents and interventions from 900 years.",
