    lat: 51.7197,
    lng: -1.544,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Recorded in Christine Bloxham's Oxfordshire folklore sources: Bampton held a belief that on 31 October, if you stood at the west door of St Mary's church at midnight and watched in silence, you could discover who would die in the coming year. A procession of all sick and elderly villagers would file into the church. A second procession would then emerge — only those who would survive. Anyone who entered but did not reappear was doomed. This is a specific local variant of the 'church porch watch' family of Halloween divination traditions found across Britain and Ireland. It is no longer actively practised, but the west door of St Mary's is still there — and on a dark October night in a quiet market town, the tradition's logic is not entirely abstract.",
