    description: "The lane between Bampton and Clanfield has a documented ghost: 'The Sheppard,' a figure in old-fashioned clothing who appears to solitary travellers. One account describes him as naked. The Clanfield Tavern (now The Mason's Arms, reopened October 2024) was built in 1610. The original fire-back recording the date hangs over the fireplace. In 1827, all males over 12 in the parish were legally required to attend here for the Court Leet (election of jurors). Property auctions and coroner's inquests were also held here. The Clanfield Band was formed in 1912 and played its first performance at 6am on Boxing Day — the Masons Arms was their rehearsal space. Drive or cycle Bampton to Clanfield (3 miles), pub lunch or dinner, return.",
