    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Alvescot is a quiet village 3 miles north of Buckland with two extraordinary historical footnotes. A Neolithic stone hand-axe found here was petrologically analysed in 1940 and the stone identified as epidotised tuff from Stake Pass in the Lake District — 230 miles to the north. Someone carried, traded, or gifted this stone across prehistoric Britain. On 17 September 1643, Charles I, his two sons, and Lord Falkland sheltered at Butlers Court, Alvescot, during the march from Gloucester. Falkland was killed at the second Battle of Newbury three days later. Alvescot was among the last places Falkland rested in peace. The village church of St Peter (Norman chancel) is usually open. Combine with a walk to Clanfield and the Mason's Arms (1.5 miles).",
