    description: "A half-day combining three connected sites. Start: the Blowing Stone in Kingston Lisle village (in the garden of a cottage on the B4507 — accessible, always there). Blow into the lower hole; a foghorn sound carries 2 miles across the valley. Alfred supposedly used it to summon his army against the Danes. Then walk 2 miles up the escarpment to the Ridgeway. Walk east 1.5 miles to: Uffington White Horse (110m, 3,000 years old). Continue 200m to Dragon Hill (the flat-topped mound where St George supposedly killed the dragon — the bald patch at the top is where the dragon's blood fell and nothing has grown since). Descent via the combe to Woolstone village and the White Horse Inn (Tom Brown's Schooldays was written here — Thomas Hughes, 1857).",
