    description: "Childrey Brook is a chalk stream — its source (a winterbourne spring) appears from beneath the chalk ridge at Childrey village, 6 miles south of Buckland. In wet years the spring flows from May; in dry years it may not appear until November. The spring source, accessible via public footpath in a field below the Ridgeway, is where water emerges cold and clear from solid chalk. Walk from Childrey village south 2 miles to the spring source, then up the escarpment to the Ridgeway. Return via the vale path. In summer the stream is home to water-crowfoot, watercress (natural), and in the right conditions brown trout fingerlings. The village itself has the Devil's Punchbowl — a named landscape feature with no attached legend, which is itself a form of legend.",
