    lng: -1.5100,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "The Thames between Tadpole Bridge and Rushey Lock has one of the largest water vole populations in Oxfordshire. Frame it for children as a detective mission: water voles leave secret messages. Walk the Thames Path bank slowly and look for: round burrow holes (5–8cm across) just above the waterline; neatly nibbled 'lawns' of grass stems at burrow entrances; latrines — small piles of droppings on waterside tussocks that mark territory. Listen for the distinctive quiet 'plop' of a vole entering the water. Each clue you find is worth a point. The 8-year-old can be chief detective; the 6-year-old finds the burrows.",
    whyCurious: "Water voles — Ratty from Wind in the Willows — are Britain's fastest-declining mammal. This stretch of Thames is one of their strongholds in Oxfordshire. Walking quietly here in May or June, you have a genuine chance of seeing one: small, brown, blunt-faced, swimming busily along the bank.",
    familySuitability: "Good for ages 4 and up. Walk quietly and slowly. The 2-year-old must be carried near the bank. Best April–October, early morning or late afternoon.",
