    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7010,
    lng: -1.5450,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "The thick ancient hedgerows along the B4019 between Buckland and Radcot, and along the Thames Path itself, are among the best blackberrying hedgerows in the area. In late August to mid-September, a child with a tupperware tub can fill it within 20 minutes. The hedgerows here are ancient (multi-species, centuries old) and the blackberries are large, reliably sweet, and abundant. Give each child their own container and the rule: you have to eat two for every five you pick. Frame it as: 'We're going to collect enough blackberries to make a crumble tonight.' Come home and make it immediately.",
    whyCurious: "The folklore rule is that blackberries must be picked before Michaelmas (29 September) — after that date the devil has spat on them. This is probably why they go mushy in October. The hedgerows along this route are old enough to contain field maple, spindle, hawthorn, blackthorn, and dog rose alongside the blackberry — each one a clue to the hedge's age.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for all ages. The 2-year-old eats more than they pick. The 6 and 8-year-old are competitive. Bring tupperware containers and wear old clothes. Late August to mid-September.",
