    name: "Brown Hare Boxing Match: Dawn Watch in March",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.6850,
    lng: -1.4400,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "On an open arable field edge near Charney Bassett or Longworth, in March, arrive one hour before sunrise and scan the field. Bring binoculars. Look for pairs or groups of brown hares chasing each other across the open ground — the famous 'boxing' is females fending off males. Park at a gate at the field edge; don't enter the field. The 8-year-old navigates, the 6-year-old is first spotter. The experience — watching something genuinely wild and frantic happening just 200 metres away in the early grey light — is one of the great free wildlife experiences of the English countryside.",
    whyCurious: "Hares don't hibernate and are most visible and active in March, when mating competition is at its peak. They're not rabbits — a hare is much larger, has longer ears with black tips, and runs faster than a dog. They were considered magical creatures in British folklore; killing one was considered extremely unlucky in many parts of England.",
    familySuitability: "Works best for ages 6 and 8 who can maintain quiet and stillness for 20 minutes. The 2-year-old in a carrier or car seat. Early start required (dawn). March only.",
