    name: "Harvest Mice Nest Hunt: Find the World's Smallest House",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7085,
    lng: -1.4895,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "In August and September, walk the reed bed edges at Chimney Meadows and search for harvest mouse nests. These are tennis-ball-sized spheres of woven grass, attached to reed stems about 40–60cm above ground, with a small entrance hole. The mice themselves are tiny (4–6g) and rarely seen, but the nests are visible if you know what to look for. Frame it: 'We're going to find the world's smallest house.' Bring a hand lens. If you find a nest, photograph it but don't touch — it may be occupied. The 8-year-old can measure the height above ground; the 6-year-old spots the sphere shape.",
