    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.6990,
    lng: -1.5310,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Walk a half-mile section of Thames bank near Rushey Lock and identify every distinct smell: wild mint in wet patches (crush a leaf — immediately recognisable), meadowsweet at the bank edge (sweet almond scent, June–August), decaying weed behind a lock sill (not unpleasant — earthy), the muddy sweetness of an exposed riverbank, the green freshness of the river itself. Everyone agrees on a name for each smell and marks it on a hand-drawn map of the bank. At the end, cover someone's eyes and lead them to each smell point — can they identify it blindfolded? The 6-year-old will take to this immediately.",
    whyCurious: "Meadowsweet — white-flowered, waist-high along the Thames bank from June onwards — was strewn on the floors of great halls in Tudor times because of its scent. It was also Queen Elizabeth I's favourite strewing herb. The same plant grows in exactly the same places along this stretch of river as it has for centuries.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for all ages. The 2-year-old participates fully — they have excellent smell sensitivity. This activity costs nothing and requires nothing except attentiveness. Best June–August when the bank flora is at its richest.",
