    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7015,
    lng: -1.5170,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Each child finds a straight stick and marks it with mud rings every 10cm. At the safe shallow margins of the Thames near Tadpole Bridge (use the bank, not the channel), measure the depth at five different points: the very edge, 30cm in, under a willow root, in a small backwater, and in the current if you can reach safely. Record each measurement. Then draw a cross-section profile of the riverbed. Where is it shallowest? Where deepest? Is there a pattern? The 8-year-old can design the experiment; the 6-year-old makes the measurements; the 2-year-old paddles in the shallowest margin.",
    whyCurious: "Rivers are deepest on the outside of bends where the current scours the bank, and shallowest on the inside where sediment is deposited. This is basic river geomorphology — and it's completely invisible from the surface. The depth stick reveals the river's hidden architecture.",
    familySuitability: "Works well with the 8-year-old taking the lead. The 2-year-old can paddle in the shallowest sections. Wellies essential. The Thames here is not for swimming — the current is deceptive — but marginal paddling at the bank edge is fine.",
