    lng: -1.4660,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "On a clear sunny day, push a straight stick into the ground in the middle of a flat, open field south of Buckland. Mark the tip of the shadow with a pebble. Wait 15 minutes. Mark it again. Wait another 15 and mark again. You now have a sun clock — the shadow sweeps from west toward east as the sun moves. The line from the stick tip through the last pebble marks east. Can the 8-year-old figure out what time it is from the third mark's position? (North is directly behind the stick at noon; east is 90° to the right in the morning.) There are flat open fields all around the village.",
    whyCurious: "The sun dial was humanity's first precision timekeeping technology — Stonehenge is essentially a shadow clock. This is the same principle that medieval farmers used to time their working day. And it works. Your pebble marks are genuinely accurate to within 20 minutes.",
    familySuitability: "Works brilliantly for the 8-year-old. The 6-year-old places the pebbles. The 2-year-old moves the pebbles. Requires only a stick and 30 minutes of patience. Any open field south of Buckland on a sunny day.",
    bestFor: "Science, history, sunny days, ages 6 and up",
