    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7050,
    lng: -1.4900,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Walk 30 paces (approximately 25 metres) along any thick, gnarled hedgerow between Buckland and Hinton Waldrist. Count the number of different woody species you can identify: hawthorn, blackthorn, field maple, elder, hazel, dog rose, spindle, crab apple. Each species found in your 30 paces represents approximately 100 years of age — this is Hooper's Rule, published by the ecologist Max Hooper in 1974. Find 6 species: your hedge is roughly 600 years old. Find 8: it dates to around 1200 AD. Compare two different hedgerow sections. Which is older? The 8-year-old can look up unfamiliar species on a plant ID app.",
    whyCurious: "Hooper's Rule is genuinely useful — it has been independently verified across thousands of British hedgerows. The ancient hedgerow network in the Vale of White Horse is one of the better-preserved in lowland England. You can date the landscape by counting leaves.",
    familySuitability: "Works for ages 7 and up. The 6-year-old counts; the 8-year-old identifies species. Bring a tree ID app (Seek or PlantNet) or a field guide. Best April–October when leaves are visible.",
