    name: "Flood Debris Transect: What Does the River Carry?",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7085,
    lng: -1.4905,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "After a flood retreats from Chimney Meadows (usually February–March), the high-water line leaves a ridge of debris 5–10cm high: twigs, seeds, dead grass, a feather, insect cases, the occasional plastic bottle. Walk along this 'tide line' for 100 metres and collect everything interesting into separate piles: seeds, animal material, human litter, woody material, unidentifiable objects. Count each pile. Weigh them if you brought scales. What does the river carry? Where did it come from? The 8-year-old sorts and counts; the 6-year-old carries the bags.",
    whyCurious: "A flood debris line is a direct record of what happened upstream — seeds from plants 20 miles away in the Cotswolds, bark from fallen trees in the Cirencester area, litter from towns on the tributaries. Reading it is like reading a letter from upriver.",
