    description: "Faringdon's Tuesday Farmers' Market runs on the first Tuesday of every month, 8:30am–1pm, in the Market Place. Stallholders sell: local trout (from the Cotswolds), farmhouse cheese, soft fruit in season, bread, cakes, cut flowers, plants, and a refill store. The regular Tuesday market runs every week (non-farmers'-market weeks have general market stalls). Frame it for children: each child has a budget (50p–£1) and must buy one thing from the market with their own money. The 6-year-old will agonise beautifully. Faringdon has held a Tuesday market since 1313.",
    whyCurious: "Faringdon received its market charter in 1218 — it has been a market town for over 800 years. The same market day (Tuesday) has run continuously since the 13th century. When your children buy a piece of cheese in the market square, they are participating in a commercial tradition older than the English language they're speaking.",
