    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.6860,
    lng: -1.4160,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "In January and February, snowdrops appear in Buckland's own churchyard and along the lane edges. Start at home: count how many snowdrop clumps are in the church graveyard. Then drive to Kingston Bagpuize House (4 miles east) which holds an annual Snowdrop and Plant Fair in late February — the grounds have mature woodland scattered with snowdrop drifts. The children's challenge: who can find the most double-flowered snowdrop (the unusual form with extra petals inside)? Snowdrops are one of the very few wild plants that push through frozen ground.",
    whyCurious: "Snowdrops are not native to Britain — they were almost certainly introduced by medieval monasteries. The date they flower marks the exact midpoint between the winter solstice and the spring equinox — which is why it coincides with Candlemas (2 February). Finding the first snowdrop of the year has been considered lucky since the Middle Ages.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for all ages. Short walks, no climbing. The 2-year-old can be carried. January–February. Kingston Bagpuize House: check kbhevents.uk for snowdrop fair dates.",
