    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.6930,
    lng: -1.5840,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "The backwater channel at Radcot — the old Thames stream under the medieval three-arched bridge, now carrying only a fraction of the river's flow — is the shallowest and most sheltered paddling spot in the area. In summer, the depth varies from ankle to knee. The Ye Olde Swan island is flat, the current is barely perceptible, and the water is relatively warm in August. Paddle in wellies or bare feet from the bank. The 2-year-old can splash safely while the older children do Poohsticks from the medieval arch above. The Swan's garden is on the island for lunch.",
    whyCurious: "This backwater was the main channel of the Thames until 1787, when the navigation cut was dug. Before then, every boat on the upper Thames had to navigate this medieval archway. Now it carries slow backwater and children's feet.",
    familySuitability: "Best paddling spot in the area specifically for the 2-year-old. Bring a change of clothes. August is best when the water level is lower and warmer. Supervision essential — keep the 2-year-old well away from the main navigation channel.",
