    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7090,
    lng: -1.4800,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "The Thames floodplain between Buckland and the river is almost perfectly flat — an unusual landscape that creates strange visual opportunities. Each child has a phone camera and must take: (a) the most interesting photo using only the flat horizon and sky — no foreground objects, (b) a photo where a person looks as tall as a tree in the distance, (c) a photo that makes a buttercup look the size of a house (put the camera at ground level 2cm from the flower), (d) a photo where the sky takes up more than 75% of the frame. Review all entries together and vote for each category winner.",
    whyCurious: "The flat Vale of White Horse floodplain is the kind of landscape that usually only photographers notice — it forces you to think about sky, scale, and distance in ways that hilly country never does. The extreme flatness was created by thousands of years of Thames flooding depositing silt, raising the valley floor while the surrounding hills were cut by erosion.",
