    name: "Stick Mandala and Leaf Spiral in Buckland Warren",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7000,
    lng: -1.5240,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "In autumn (October–November), Buckland Warren's floor is covered in a deep leaf litter of oak, ash, and hazel leaves. Collect leaves, sticks, and acorns. Make a mandala on a flat patch of ground: start with a central acorn, surround it with a ring of same-colour leaves, then alternate rings of sticks and leaves spiralling outward. Or build a spiral of alternating oak and ash leaves. The rule: use only what you find on the ground. Leave it for other walkers. Photograph it from directly above. The 8-year-old designs; the 6-year-old builds; the 2-year-old contributes enthusiastically in a chaotic way.",
    whyCurious: "Temporary land art in woodland — inspired by the artist Andy Goldsworthy, who works exclusively with natural materials — has a long tradition in British environmental art. The materials are free, the result is genuinely beautiful, and its disappearance (wind, rain, other walkers) is part of the point.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for all ages. The 2-year-old participates at their own level. Requires nothing except the materials on the ground. Best October–November when the leaf litter is deepest. Allow 30–45 minutes.",
