    name: "Stone Procession Along the Thames Shallows at Grafton",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.6990,
    lng: -1.5100,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "At the gravelly margins of the Thames near Old Man's Bridge (the wooden footbridge between Tadpole Bridge and Rushey Lock), river-washed pebbles and stones of different sizes, colours, and textures can be collected safely from the bank. Build a procession: arrange stones from the smallest you can find to the largest you can carry, in a line along the bank edge. The 2-year-old carries and places; the 8-year-old arranges in exact size order; the 6-year-old finds the most interesting shapes. Then the river edge washes it away — fleeting art. Return in 30 minutes and see what remains.",
    whyCurious: "The Thames gravel here is Thames Valley gravel — worn smooth over thousands of years of flowing water. The different colours come from different source rocks: white quartzite from the Cotswolds, red-brown ironstone from Jurassic beds, grey flint from chalk. Every stone has a geological biography.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for all ages including the 2-year-old. Wellies or bare feet. Completely safe at the bank margin — keep children away from the current in the main channel. Any season.",
