    name: "Puddle Paddling in Flood Retreat at Chimney Meadows",
    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7085,
    lng: -1.4905,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "As flood water retreats from Chimney Meadows in late February or March, it leaves behind shallow, warm-ish puddles in tyre ruts and hollows — perfect for toddler wading in wellies. The 2-year-old wades with impunity in puddles 5–10cm deep while the 6 and 8-year-old hunt the same puddles for tadpoles and water beetles. Bring a white plastic tray: pour a scoop of puddle water into it and hold it up to the light. You'll see water boatmen, pond skaters, diving beetles, and possibly frog eggs or tiny tadpoles. A magnifying glass is useful.",
    whyCurious: "Flood retreat puddles are temporary ecosystems that appear and disappear on a timescale of days to weeks. Aquatic insects — already present in the soil as eggs and larvae — activate immediately when water appears. A puddle that existed only 48 hours earlier can already contain 8–10 invertebrate species.",
    familySuitability: "Perfect for the 2-year-old specifically — safe depth, contained, endlessly interesting. All children will get completely muddy. February–March. Bring multiple plastic trays and a magnifying glass.",
