    description: "Grass snakes are large (up to a metre), harmless, and live in exactly this landscape: warm, wet flood meadow margins near the Thames, compost heaps, the edges of cut vegetation piles, and south-facing embankments. In April–September, walk slowly along the south-facing margins of the Thames Path between Chimney Meadows and Tadpole Bridge, looking in long grass, under flat boards or corrugated iron left by the path side, and on cut vegetation piles warmed by the sun. They flee quickly but dramatically. If you find one, photograph immediately. Frame it: 'We're going to look for a dragon.'",
