    description: "In March and April, the drainage ditches beside the footpaths around Charney Bassett burst into flower with marsh marigolds — large, chrome-yellow flowers that grow right at the water's edge. Walk from Charney Bassett village along the Ock footpath and count how many marsh marigold clumps you can spot. Challenge: find the largest single flower. Also look for lesser celandine (smaller, starry yellow), and if you're there in mid-April, the first cuckooflower (pale lilac, food plant of the orange-tip butterfly). The 2-year-old sees yellow in all directions. March–April only.",
