    description: "The Common Clubtail dragonfly (Gomphus vulgatissimus) is nationally scarce and the Thames from Tadpole Bridge to Shifford is one of its strongholds. In May and June, walk the Thames Path on a warm sunny morning and watch low over the river — Clubtails fly low and fast, settling on bankside vegetation. They are yellow-and-black, with a distinctively clubbed tail. A confirmed sighting is unusual enough to log on iNaturalist — photograph if possible and upload. The challenge: can you find one? Many visits won't produce one; a sighting feels genuinely lucky.",
    whyCurious: "The Common Clubtail has declined dramatically nationally because it requires unpolluted, silt-bedded rivers — the Thames from here to Lechlade is one of the few stretches that still qualifies. Many UK records come from Oxfordshire. Finding one here is finding a species that is genuinely struggling to survive.",
    familySuitability: "Works for patient older children (8-year-old specifically). The 2-year-old adds chaotic energy. Download iNaturalist before you go. May–June only, warm sunny mornings, walking slowly.",
    bestFor: "Dragonflies, rarity, citizen science, May–June, ages 8 and up",
