    description: "Duxford Ford is where an ancient track crossed the Thames — the ford is described in Thames Path walking guides as 'a quite popular area for swimming' and is the traditional bathing point for this stretch of river. Walking to it from the Chimney Meadows car park takes about 30 minutes along the Thames Path. At low summer water levels, the ford creates shallow, clear water over gravel — the best conditions for paddling. The Duxford Old River meander running alongside (now the BBOWT nature reserve channel) creates a quieter backwater section. Check conditions before paddling and never in flood or high water.",
    whyCurious: "Every community on the upper Thames had its traditional bathing spot before swimming pools existed — the ford or the gentlest riverside bank. Duxford Ford was that place for the communities of Bampton and Chimney. People swam here on summer evenings for centuries before the lock era changed the river's character.",
    familySuitability: "Works in summer (July–September) at low water only. The gravel ford is the safest paddling here. Never enter when the river is high or flowing fast. Keep the 2-year-old on a very tight rein at the water's edge. Access on foot from Chimney Meadows car park.",
