    category: "adventures",
    lat: 51.7000,
    lng: -1.5235,
    type: "Adventure Idea",
    description: "Arrive at Buckland Warren at 5am in May (1 mile from Buckland village — walking distance). As the sky lightens, the woodland dawn chorus builds through recognisable stages: the nuthatch (a descending whistle), the treecreeper (very high-pitched, often missed), the great spotted woodpecker drumming on a dead branch (10–20 rapid beats), then blackcaps (the most beautiful warbler song in Britain — fluid, loud, varied), chiffchaffs, and finally the full choir. This is gentler than the Chimney Meadows wetland version — calmer, more intimate, easier with the 2-year-old.",
    whyCurious: "Scientists have shown that the order of the dawn chorus is fixed: robins always start first (40 minutes before sunrise), then blackbirds, then the other species join in sequence. By the time you reach the wood's edge at 5am, the first layer is already singing. Each species adds its voice at a precise, predictable time.",
    familySuitability: "Works from 1 mile — no car needed. The 2-year-old can go in a carrier. The 8-year-old can time species arrivals and note the sequence. Bring a flask of hot chocolate. May only.",
