    name: "Natural History Museum — The Oxford Dodo Skull",
    lat: 51.7591,
    lng: -1.2563,
    category: "rainy-day",
    type: "museum",
    description: "The Oxford University Museum of Natural History holds the only surviving soft tissue of a dodo anywhere in the world — a head and foot, obtained in the 1650s and displayed in a case in the main hall. The specimen directly inspired Lewis Carroll, who was a regular visitor, to include a dodo in Alice's Adventures in Wonderland.",
    whyCurious: "Carroll (Charles Dodgson) stammered slightly and sometimes introduced himself as 'Do-Do-Dodgson.' The dodo in Alice is understood by scholars to be a self-portrait. He visited this museum frequently and the specific specimen is what he saw. The foot is next to the head in the same case.",
