    name: "Iffley Lock — Thames's Most Photographed Lock",
    lat: 51.7319,
    lng: -1.2412,
    category: "nature",
    type: "lock",
    description: "Iffley Lock, 2km south of Christ Church, is one of the oldest pound locks on the Thames (rebuilt 1924) and sits next to a weir, a lock cottage with a garden, and a natural backwater. The lock keeper tends a prize-winning garden around the lock chamber. The cottage has won the Thames Path 'best lock garden' competition multiple times.",
    whyCurious: "Almost no tourists come this far south on foot. The weir pool at Iffley is one of the best spots in Oxford for seeing kingfishers — the turbulent water below the weir concentrates small fish. Arrive at dawn in summer and stand still for 10 minutes. The lock keeper occasionally emerges and tells you exactly where the nest is.",
