    name: "St Mary the Virgin — The City's Secret Roof Terrace",
    lat: 51.7519,
    lng: -1.2527,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "church",
    description: "The University Church of St Mary the Virgin on the High Street has a tower open to visitors for a small fee. The climb ends on an external walkway 18 metres up with a 360-degree view of the city — the Radcliffe Camera below you, All Souls to the east, Christ Church to the south. It is the best rooftop view in Oxford and costs less than a coffee.",
    whyCurious: "John Henry Newman preached from this pulpit, C.S. Lewis gave his famous 'The Weight of Glory' sermon here in 1941, and the Martyrs Cranmer, Latimer and Ridley were tried in the nave before being burned outside. The porch has a column deliberately twisted by 17th-century masons — no one knows exactly why.",
