    name: "New College Garden — The City Wall You Can Walk Along",
    lat: 51.7539,
    lng: -1.2503,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "garden",
    description: "New College garden contains the finest surviving stretch of Oxford's medieval city wall, built in 1226. The college was founded in 1379 with a specific obligation to maintain the wall — still legally binding today. The garden path runs along the top of the wall's inner bank, giving a walkway 3 metres above the garden.",
    whyCurious: "This stretch of medieval fortification is free to enter during college visiting hours and is far less visited than the rest of New College. In summer, deer graze in the mound beyond the wall — the mound itself is a Black Death plague burial site from 1349, never excavated.",
