    name: "Pitt Rivers Museum — The Witch Bottles Cabinet",
    lat: 51.7588,
    lng: -1.2556,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "museum",
    description: "Deep in the Pitt Rivers Museum is a cabinet of witch bottles — sealed pottery or glass containers filled with urine, hair, nail clippings, and bent pins, buried under hearths or thresholds in 16th–18th century England to repel witches. The collection includes examples found during building work in Oxford itself.",
    whyCurious: "The museum displays them matter-of-factly alongside the instructions for how they were supposed to work. Several were found during renovations to Oxford college buildings in the 20th century, suggesting the practice continued in academic households long after the Enlightenment. The pins inside are still perfectly preserved.",
