    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "museum",
    description: "The Pitt Rivers Museum holds a collection of reliquaries and memorial hair — including a locket of hair reputedly from King Charles I, taken at his execution in 1649, and several Victorian mourning brooches containing the braided hair of loved ones. They are in the amulets and charms section, small enough to miss.",
    whyCurious: "Victorian mourning hair jewellery was so common that the museum has dozens of examples — rings, brooches, pendants — all containing human hair woven into flowers or plaited into watchfobs. The label next to each piece is written in the original donor's handwriting, which makes it unexpectedly intimate.",
