    name: "The King's Arms — Oxford's Academic Pub",
    lat: 51.7543,
    lng: -1.2531,
    category: "food-or-treats",
    type: "pub",
    description: "The King's Arms on Holywell Street, open since 1607, was the first pub in Oxford to admit women (in 1973, a year before the Equal Opportunities Act forced the issue elsewhere). It sits opposite the Sheldonian and Weston Library and was the preferred pub of Isaiah Berlin, A.J. Ayer, and much of Oxford philosophy's golden generation.",
    whyCurious: "The pub's long wooden tables are still arranged for argument — long benches facing each other. A.J. Ayer once challenged a man who was being aggressive toward a model at a party: the man was Mike Tyson. Ayer said, 'I am the Wykeham Professor of Logic. We are both distinguished men.' True story, attested by several witnesses.",
