    name: "Holywell Music Room — The World's Oldest Concert Hall",
    lat: 51.7553,
    lng: -1.2532,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "concert-hall",
    description: "The Holywell Music Room on Holywell Street opened in 1748, making it the oldest purpose-built concert hall in the world still in regular use. It seats 200, has near-perfect acoustics for chamber music, and operates a regular series of lunchtime concerts. Handel is believed to have performed here.",
    whyCurious: "Tickets for lunchtime concerts cost around £5-10. The room is plain almost to severity — bare walls, wooden chairs, a plain stage — which makes the acoustics feel all the more remarkable. You can hear a quartet here for less than the price of a cinema ticket in a room older than any surviving concert hall in Vienna.",
