    lng: -1.2560,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "library",
    description: "The Weston Library (opened 2015, converted from the New Bodleian) has a free public exhibition gallery on the ground floor showing rotating selections from the Bodleian's special collections — manuscripts, early printed books, musical scores, maps. The atrium cafe is also free to enter. The building's glazed interior courtyard is one of Oxford's great modern spaces.",
    whyCurious: "The exhibitions regularly include items almost never publicly displayed — Shelley's draft manuscripts, Shakespeare first folios, the original score of a Mozart symphony. Entry is free and no booking required. The Bodleian is best known for the historic buildings nearby; almost no one knows this contemporary branch exists.",
