    lng: -1.3133,
    category: "nature",
    type: "woodland",
    description: "Wytham Woods, 4km west of Oxford, is 420 hectares of ancient semi-natural woodland owned by the university and the most intensively studied piece of woodland on Earth — Oxford scientists have been monitoring its ecology continuously since 1942. The public can access it via a free permit obtained online from the University.",
    whyCurious: "Every tree in Wytham over a certain size has been individually tagged and measured. The long-term dataset on great tit populations here (80+ years continuous) is the basis for much of what is known about natural selection in wild bird populations. You walk through an open-air laboratory — the nest boxes have individual numbers and records going back decades.",
