    description: "Wolvercote Common is a small area of unimproved damp grassland between Wolvercote village and the Oxford Canal, north of Port Meadow. It is a local nature reserve with marsh orchids, yellow rattle, and ragged robin in June. The Two Rivers Way long-distance footpath passes through it, connecting Port Meadow to the Thames above Oxford.",
    whyCurious: "Few Oxford residents know Wolvercote Common exists independently of Port Meadow. The common has a distinct flora because it floods from canal rather than river, giving it slightly different soil chemistry. In June the marsh orchids can exceed 200 flowering plants in a space no bigger than a tennis court.",
