    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "public-art",
    description: "The 13 stone busts on pillars outside the Sheldonian Theatre on Broad Street — the 'Emperors' or 'Philosophers' — depict bearded figures with no labels and no agreed-upon identity. Scholars have proposed they represent Roman emperors, the Apostles, and even a generic parade of philosophy. They have been replaced multiple times; the current versions are from 2007.",
    whyCurious: "The original 1669 heads eroded so badly by the early 19th century that William Combe wrote a satirical poem about their decrepitude. John Betjeman called the current versions 'blank-eyed gods.' Max Beerbohm used them in a novel. Nobody — not the University, not art historians — agrees on who they are supposed to be.",
