    type: "pub",
    description: "The Bookbinders Arms on Victor Street in Jericho is a two-room Victorian backstreet pub that has changed almost nothing since the 1970s. It serves real ales from regional breweries, has no music, no fruit machines, and no screens — just conversation and a small beer garden behind. It was the local for Oxford University Press workers for generations.",
    whyCurious: "The pub is a ten-minute walk from the tourist centre and almost never has a tourist inside it. The name refers directly to the Oxford University Press bookbinding workshop 200 metres away — the workers who bound Bibles and learned texts by hand were the regulars here. A photo of the original OUP bindery women is on the back wall.",
