    description: "Old Marston village, 2km east of the city centre, retains its medieval layout — a church, a pub, a duck pond, and a cluster of thatched and stone cottages around a village green — despite being technically within the Oxford city boundary. The village was where Royalist forces camped during the Civil War siege of Oxford (1646).",
    whyCurious: "The manor house in Marston was used as headquarters for the Parliamentary siege — the rooms where the terms of Oxford's surrender were negotiated still exist. The village pub (The Victoria Arms) has a riverside garden on the Cherwell accessible only by foot or punt and is one of the most pleasant pub gardens in Oxfordshire.",
