    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "historic-building",
    description: "St Edmund Hall (Oxford's smallest college) has a medieval well in its main quad, believed to be Saxon in origin and still producing water. The well dates to before the college's foundation in the 13th century and is one of the few surviving Saxon water sources in central Oxford. The chapel above it contains fragments of pre-Reformation stained glass.",
    whyCurious: "The well is in the centre of the smallest medieval quad in Oxford. The hall's great virtue is being genuinely unadorned — no Victorian restoration, no added grandeur — so the medieval structure is more legible here than almost anywhere else. The chapel has a painted reredos by William Dyce almost unknown to art historians.",
