    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "historic-building",
    description: "The passageways of the Covered Market area follow the medieval 'meat shambles' layout — the word 'shambles' means a slaughterhouse or butchers' row. The current Market Street and its side alleys preserve the footprint of the medieval trading rows that occupied this site from 1200 onwards. Butchers still trade in the same location.",
    whyCurious: "Oxford's streets in this zone are confusing to navigate precisely because they follow medieval property boundaries, not any rational plan. The short alley connecting the Covered Market to the High Street (the old Golden Cross Inn yard) is a medieval coaching yard still bounded by 15th-century timber-framed walls on two sides.",
