    category: "rainy-day",
    type: "museum",
    description: "The Story Museum on Pembroke Street occupies a late Georgian building and focuses entirely on children's literature and storytelling, with permanent installations exploring Oxford's unique role in children's fiction — Alice, Narnia, His Dark Materials, Wind in the Willows (written partly in Oxford). Interactive exhibits use theatre, art, and immersive spaces.",
    whyCurious: "Oxford has produced more canonical children's literature per square mile than almost any other city in the world. The museum traces the connections — Carroll's Christ Church, Tolkien's Northmoor Road, Pullman's Jordan College, Grahame's Pangbourne nearby — and shows the actual places that became fictional ones. The building itself has a secret door.",
