    name: "St Giles' Church — A Saxon Foundation Older Than the University",
    lat: 51.7577,
    lng: -1.2637,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "church",
    description: "St Giles' Church at the north end of St Giles' Street has a Saxon foundation — a stone from the original 10th-century church is incorporated into the current 13th-century building. The churchyard, shaded by ancient lime trees, forms the central reservation of St Giles' Street during the week and the site of St Giles' Fair in September.",
    whyCurious: "The church predates the university by at least 200 years, making it a reminder that Oxford was a market town and ecclesiastical centre long before it was an academic one. The churchyard contains the grave of C.S. Lewis's father and — on the east wall — a memorial to William Ayloffe, an Oxford physician who wrote early texts on statistics.",
