    name: "Philippa Foot's Grave — The Trolley Problem Philosopher",
    lat: 51.7913,
    lng: -1.2721,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "cemetery",
    description: "Wolvercote Cemetery, north Oxford, contains the grave of Philippa Foot (1920–2010), the moral philosopher who invented the trolley problem thought experiment in her 1967 paper. The trolley problem — would you divert a runaway trolley to kill one person instead of five — is now one of the most discussed scenarios in ethics globally.",
    whyCurious: "Foot's paper is the origin of a philosophical thought experiment now referenced in discussions of self-driving car ethics, military AI, and medical triage worldwide. Her grave is modest and unadorned in a municipal cemetery. Nearby is the grave of J.R.R. Tolkien and his wife Edith, who are buried together under the names Beren and Luthien.",
