    description: "J.R.R. Tolkien and his wife Edith are buried together in Wolvercote Cemetery, north Oxford. Their headstone gives their real names but adds 'Beren' under Tolkien's name and 'Luthien' under Edith's — the names of the mortal man and immortal elf whose love story in The Silmarillion Tolkien described as the central story of his mythology, inspired by Edith.",
    whyCurious: "Tolkien wrote to his son in 1971 about Edith: 'She was the Luthien Tinuviel of my life.' She died in 1971; he died in 1973. The names were added at his request. Fans leave small stones, flowers, and handwritten notes on the grave. The cemetery map is available from the office; the grave is in Section 1.",
