    name: "Oxford Gargoyles — The Screaming Faces of All Souls",
    lat: 51.7524,
    lng: -1.2510,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "public-art",
    description: "The north face of All Souls College on High Street has the most expressive gargoyles in Oxford — faces contorted in what appear to be screams, grimaces, and expressions of profound suffering. The medieval grotesques were intended to ward off evil spirits; the All Souls ones are particularly extreme in their anguish and can be closely examined from the pavement.",
    whyCurious: "Medieval stonemasons were given relative freedom in carving gargoyles, as they were considered outside the main decorative scheme. The All Souls grotesques are thought to include portraits of actual 15th-century individuals — possibly including a hunchback known to have worked on the site. Binoculars help; the best faces are in the second-storey level.",
