    name: "Port Meadow Wildfowl — What Arrives When",
    lat: 51.7730,
    lng: -1.2800,
    category: "nature",
    type: "meadow",
    description: "Port Meadow's flooded winter surface attracts a precise succession of wildfowl: Bewick's swans arrive from Siberia in October; whooper swans from Iceland follow in November; wigeon, teal, shoveler and pintail ducks peak in December-January; dunlin and snipe are present in the wet margins from September to March. The meadow is best at dawn with a south wind.",
    whyCurious: "The Bewick's swans that use Port Meadow are individually identifiable by their bill patterns — the Wildfowl and Wetlands Trust has identified the same individual swans returning to this meadow over multiple winters. You could, in theory, be looking at a bird that has made the 2,500km journey from the Yamal Peninsula to this Oxford field for 20+ years.",
