    name: "Wadham College Garden — The Secret Walled Space",
    lat: 51.7554,
    lng: -1.2543,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "garden",
    description: "Wadham College's garden, entered from the main quad, is a large walled space with mature trees, herbaceous borders, and a lawn that is open to visitors during college hours. The garden is rarely listed in tourist guides. Wadham was founded in 1610 by Dorothy Wadham, one of the very few women to have founded an Oxford college before the 20th century.",
    whyCurious: "The garden has an unusual history as a meeting place — the group that became the Royal Society met in Warden Wilkins's lodgings at Wadham in the 1650s, and their experimental apparatus was kept in the garden. Christopher Wren was a member of this group and designed experimental equipment that was tested here before he became an architect.",
