    name: "Museum of the History of Science — The Blackboard Einstein Used",
    lat: 51.7543,
    lng: -1.2553,
    category: "rainy-day",
    type: "museum",
    description: "The Museum of the History of Science on Broad Street (free entry) occupies the original Ashmolean building of 1683. It holds Einstein's blackboard — a chalk-covered board from a 1931 Oxford lecture, preserved exactly as he left it, equations still visible. It also contains the earliest surviving astrolabes, Lewis Carroll's photographic equipment, and Marconi's wireless apparatus.",
    whyCurious: "The blackboard was never wiped after Einstein's lecture — the person responsible for cleaning it refused to do so on the grounds that it was now a historical document. The equations on it relate to the expanding universe and the cosmological constant. The board is in the ground-floor gallery and is one of the most unexpectedly moving objects in Oxford.",
