    name: "The Isis Farmhouse — Oxford's Most Remote City Pub",
    lat: 51.7308,
    lng: -1.2412,
    category: "food-or-treats",
    type: "pub",
    description: "The Isis Farmhouse pub at Iffley is accessible only on foot or by punt — there is no car access. It sits on the west bank of the Thames immediately below Iffley Lock, with a waterside garden and a simple menu. The walk from Folly Bridge takes 30 minutes along the Thames Path; many people walk down and punt back.",
    whyCurious: "The farmhouse was built as an actual farm serving river traffic in the 19th century. It became a pub because boatmen and lock-keepers needed refreshment. The garden floods in winter and the pub closes; in summer it is one of the most pleasant spots in Oxfordshire for a drink. The only sounds are water, geese, and the lock gate mechanisms.",
