    name: "Balliol College — The Scorch Mark from the Protestant Martyrs",
    lat: 51.7541,
    lng: -1.2574,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "college",
    description: "In the outer wall of Balliol College on Broad Street, at pavement level, is a cross of dark stone set into the cobbles marking the approximate spot where Bishops Latimer and Ridley were burned at the stake in 1555 under Mary I. Cranmer was burned nearby in 1556. The marks were set in the road in the 19th century; a second monument stands in the wall.",
    whyCurious: "Most tourists photograph the Martyrs' Memorial on St Giles' (400 metres away) and miss the actual site. The spot is on the pavement outside Balliol College gate. A story persists — impossible to verify — that a scorch mark exists on the Balliol garden wall directly opposite, which has been pointed out to generations of students.",
