    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "historic-building",
    description: "The Schools Quadrangle of the Bodleian Library, entered through the Tower of the Five Orders on Catte Street, is free to enter during opening hours. The five orders of classical architecture (Tuscan, Doric, Ionic, Corinthian, Composite) are stacked vertically on the gate tower — the only example of all five displayed together on any English building.",
    whyCurious: "The gate tower is the most architecturally ambitious entrance in Oxford and most visitors walk past it on their way to the Radcliffe Camera. The quadrangle inside is used as a Bodleian reading area and is the oldest university quadrangle in continuous academic use. The doors to each faculty reading room are labelled in Latin with their original subject.",
