    name: "Pembroke College — Samuel Johnson's Oxford",
    lat: 51.7510,
    lng: -1.2558,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "college",
    description: "Samuel Johnson studied at Pembroke College from 1728 to 1729 — he left without a degree because he ran out of money. His room (on the third staircase of the Old Quad) is marked and the college displays his teapot, used when he held informal seminars for friends. The Master's Lodgings has his portrait by Joshua Reynolds.",
    whyCurious: "Johnson arrived at Oxford with a hole in his shoe and brilliant wit. When a fellow student left him a new pair of shoes outside his door anonymously, Johnson threw them away in fury at the perceived condescension. He later described his time at Oxford as among the happiest of his life and gave the college money in later years. The teapot is genuinely his.",
