    name: "Iffley Meadows Snake's Head Fritillaries — April Only",
    lat: 51.7380,
    lng: -1.2430,
    category: "nature",
    type: "nature-reserve",
    description: "Iffley Meadows Local Nature Reserve, on the east bank of the Thames at Iffley, holds one of the largest populations of snake's head fritillary (Fritillaria meleagris) in Britain — several thousand plants flowering in April. The meadow is an unimproved flood-plain grassland, never ploughed. Access is free via the Thames Path from Iffley village.",
    whyCurious: "Snake's head fritillaries are now extremely rare in Britain but were once common in Thames flood meadows. The chequered purple and white blooms are so architecturally perfect they look artificial. The best time is a sunny April morning, 10am to midday, when the flowers are fully open and the meadow appears to be carpeted with small lanterns.",
