    description: "A curious flat-topped natural chalk knoll directly below the White Horse at Uffington. The bare white circle on its summit, where no grass has ever grown, is traditionally the spot where St George slew the dragon — and where the dragon's blood fell and poisoned the ground forever. Geologically it is exposed chalk. Mythologically it is one of the oldest dragon-killing sites in England, predating the St George legend being formally attached to it by centuries.",
    whyCurious: "The grass genuinely does not grow there. The National Trust has no entirely satisfying explanation. Stand on the patch and look up at the White Horse above you and feel the full weight of the landscape's strangeness.",
