    name: "Stanford in the Vale Village Lock-Up",
    lat: 51.6391,
    lng: -1.5058,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "historic building",
    description: "A small stone lock-up — a single-cell overnight prison for drunks and minor offenders — survives in Stanford in the Vale, one of a scattering of such structures across the Vale. It dates from the late 18th century, when every parish needed somewhere to hold people before the magistrate arrived from Faringdon. The door is original ironwork. The interior is the size of a large wardrobe. It was used regularly until the 1850s.",
