    lng: -1.6677,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "model estate village",
    description: "Coleshill village exists almost entirely because of the Coleshill House estate, and has changed remarkably little since the Victorian estate rebuilding. The great house burned down in 1952, but the National Trust maintains the estate and the village retains its estate character — uniform stone cottages, tended verges, an atmosphere of suspended time. The footprint of Coleshill House itself is now a grassed outline where one of England's finest 17th century houses once stood, described by Nikolaus Pevsner as among the most important country houses in England.",
