    name: "Bampton's Unusually Intact Medieval Street Plan",
    lat: 51.7263,
    lng: -1.5459,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "historic town",
    description: "Bampton is one of those market towns that simply never grew beyond its medieval footprint. The wide main street with its market area, the church at one end, the town at the other — this is the plan of a Norman planted town and it is completely legible. The church contains a fine Saxon carved stone found reused in the fabric. The town has appeared as 'Downton' in Downton Abbey. The annual Morris dancing tradition here is one of the oldest continuously documented in England.",
    whyCurious: "Bampton's Morris tradition predates reliable recording. The Bampton Morris dancers perform in the town every Whit Monday in a tradition unbroken since at least 1700. The dances are specific to Bampton and are not performed anywhere else.",
