    name: "The Ridgeway Actual Surface Between Uffington and Bishopstone",
    lat: 51.5701,
    lng: -1.5023,
    category: "adventures",
    type: "ancient trackway",
    description: "This section of the Ridgeway retains its character as a genuine working prehistoric track — a broad rutted strip of chalk and flint up to thirty metres wide in places, not a modern path but an eroded zone where traffic over millennia has spread and reformed the route. The ruts from Victorian farm wagons are still visible alongside Bronze Age hollow ways. In winter the chalk turns to white mud that sticks to boots in plates. In summer the surface is hard white flint dust that stains walking boots grey.",
