    name: "Bourton's Deserted Village Earthworks",
    lat: 51.5831,
    lng: -1.6668,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "deserted medieval village",
    description: "To the east of Bourton village, earthworks in the adjacent fields mark the remains of a shrunken or deserted medieval settlement — the ridge-and-furrow of the open field system, hollowed trackways, and the low platforms of former house sites. The shrinkage probably occurred during the 14th-century plague and subsequent agricultural reorganisation. Nothing marks the site. A footpath crosses it and most people walking it do not realise they are threading through the ruins of a community.",
    whyCurious: "Medieval villages in England did not all survive. Hundreds shrunk and vanished, leaving only the ghost of their streets in the grassland. Walking on the earthworks is walking on the negative space of medieval lives.",
