    name: "The Ridgeway at Whitehorse Hill — Ancient Stile and Hollow Way",
    lat: 51.5756,
    lng: -1.5589,
    category: "adventures",
    type: "ancient path feature",
    description: "Just below the summit of Whitehorse Hill on the eastern approach, the Ridgeway is joined by a hollow way coming up from Woolstone — worn six feet deep into the chalk over centuries of use by people and animals coming up from the spring-line villages to the ridge road above. The junction with the Ridgeway is marked by an old stone stile, now somewhat rebuilt, but the hollow way itself is entirely original — a slot in the hillside that would have been familiar to Bronze Age travellers as much as Victorian shepherds.",
    whyCurious: "The depth of the hollow way represents ten thousand journeys. Each one wore the chalk a fraction of a millimetre. You are walking in the cumulative impression of everyone who ever climbed this hill.",
