    name: "The Roman Road Through the Vale — Ermin Street Remnants",
    lat: 51.6389,
    lng: -1.6723,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "Roman road",
    description: "Ermin Street — the Roman road from Silchester to Cirencester — runs through the northern Vale and its line is still clear in the modern road network and field boundaries near Shrivenham and Watchfield. Where the modern road deviates, the Roman alignment continues as a straight track or field edge. Near Watchfield the road runs as a slightly raised agger through a field — the cambered road surface built up by the Romans is still elevated above the surrounding ground after 1,700 years.",
    whyCurious: "The raised road surface of Ermin Street exists because the Romans built better than the centuries that followed. The agger is still there because nothing since has been worth digging it up for.",
