    name: "Faringdon's Sleeping Beauty Wood",
    lat: 51.6601,
    lng: -1.5823,
    category: "nature",
    type: "woodland",
    description: "Great Coxwell Wood and the plantations around Faringdon Folly on Folly Hill include sections of ancient woodland with a ground flora of bluebells, dog's mercury, and wood anemone — the classic indicator species of long-continuity woodland. Lord Berners planted additional specimen trees in the 1930s around the Folly. The mix of ancient understorey and eccentric parkland planting creates a woodland that feels genuinely strange in a way that reflects its owner's character.",
    whyCurious: "The wood around the Folly was planted by a man who dyed doves and put a pig mask on to church. The trees he chose are odd — specimen conifers in unexpected positions, a cedar where a beech would be. The eccentricity is botanical.",
