    name: "Uffington School — Tom Brown's Schoolroom",
    lat: 51.5834,
    lng: -1.5601,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "literary heritage",
    description: "The village school at Uffington, now a small museum, was where Thomas Hughes was educated before Rugby. Hughes set his famous novel partly here, partly at Rugby — but the childhood world described in the early chapters of Tom Brown's Schooldays is this village, this landscape, these Downs. The museum has a small collection of Hughes material and Victorian school artefacts. The building itself is relatively modest — a schoolroom that shaped one of the most widely read English novels of the 19th century.",
