    lng: -1.5189,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "railway heritage",
    description: "The Lambourn Valley Railway ran from Newbury to Lambourn from 1898 to 1960, a rural branch line that served the racing community and the villages of the valley. The trackbed survives as a walk/cycle path for much of its length, the earthworks clear — embankments, cuttings, the ghost platforms of halts that served villages with populations of a few hundred. The track was lifted in 1960 and the stationmaster's house at Lambourn is now a private residence but identifiable.",
