    category: "nature",
    type: "historic garden",
    description: "Pusey House has gardens designed in part by Geoffrey Jellicoe, with a classical layout of water, pleached limes, and rose borders that opens to the public in summer. The Irish yews planted in the 19th century have grown to extraordinary dimensions — their naturally upright fastigiate form giving them the look of huge dark exclamation marks at the corners of the garden compartments. The village of Pusey itself is estate-owned and private, adding to the enclosed, stopped-in-time quality.",
    whyCurious: "The yews are outsized for the garden — they dominate in a way their planter probably did not anticipate. A garden designed for Georgian elegance now has something gothic and slightly threatening at its corners.",
