    name: "The Corallian Limestone Ridge at Faringdon",
    lat: 51.657,
    lng: -1.586,
    category: "nature",
    type: "geological feature",
    description: "Faringdon sits on a small outlier of Corallian limestone — a harder rock than the surrounding clay — which is why the town is on a low hill and why the Folly could be built on a ridge. The Faringdon Sponge Gravels, exposed in old sand pits around the town, are famous among geologists for containing Cretaceous marine fossils of extraordinary variety — sponges, echinoids, bivalves, and shark teeth — preserved in a Lower Greensand formation. The old pit on the edge of town occasionally yields material after heavy rain.",
    whyCurious: "Faringdon's geology is more interesting than its location suggests. The town is on a rock island in a clay sea, and that island is full of Cretaceous marine creatures that lived 100 million years ago.",
