    name: "East Hendred's Catholic Chantry Chapel",
    lat: 51.5901,
    lng: -1.3867,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "medieval chapel",
    description: "East Hendred has maintained a functioning Catholic presence since the Reformation without interruption — a genuine rarity in England. The Eyston family, squires of East Hendred, remained Catholic through the penal period and the village maintained a continuous recusant tradition. The small chantry chapel of St Amand dates from the 15th century and is still in liturgical use. The village also has a museum of clocks in a historic building and one of the best-preserved late medieval street plans in the Vale.",
