    name: "The Craven Estate's Hidden Walled Garden at Ashdown",
    lat: 51.5362,
    lng: -1.5963,
    category: "hidden-places",
    type: "walled garden",
    description: "The National Trust estate at Ashdown includes a walled kitchen garden from the 18th century that is not prominently advertised. The walls themselves — high, red-brick, south-facing — retain heat and were used for training fruit trees. The garden is not fully restored but the enclosure and the surviving brick work tell the complete story of how a remote estate fed itself year-round. In the corner, a small brick building with a flue in the wall is a pinery — a structure for growing pineapples using fermenting dung as underfloor heating.",
    whyCurious: "A pinery in Berkshire. The extreme lengths an 18th century household went to for tropical fruit — fermenting horse dung to heat the floor so pineapples would grow under glass in Oxfordshire — is a specific kind of absurdity that only wealth and the pre-refrigeration era could produce.",
