    name: "The Sparsholt Firs Shelter Belt",
    lat: 51.5823,
    lng: -1.4712,
    category: "nature",
    type: "shelter belt woodland",
    description: "A long linear plantation of Scots pine and beech runs along the crest of the Downs above Sparsholt — a Victorian-era shelter belt planted to protect the downland farms from the southwest wind. From the Vale below it creates a dark horizontal line on the horizon. Inside the plantation the trees are now veteran, the floor deep in accumulated needles, and the light that filters through the canopy is green-gold in summer and gold-amber in autumn. Long-eared owls have been recorded roosting here.",
