    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "Bronze Age barrow",
    description: "Idlebush Barrow stands on the crest of the Downs southwest of Ashdown in a position of commanding visibility — from it you can see Segsbury, the Seven Barrows group, and the Uffington hillfort all on the same ridge. Its isolation and prominent position suggests it was a landmark deliberately placed for visibility rather than simply a burial site. The barrow has been dug into — a Victorian antiquarian's trench is still visible on the south side — and produced cremated remains.",
    whyCurious: "The network of barrows on the Downs is not random — they were placed to be seen from each other and from the Ridgeway. Idlebush is one of the clearest examples of a monument positioned as landscape signal rather than simply burial place.",
