    name: "The Ancient Parish Boundary Oak at Buckland",
    lat: 51.6799,
    lng: -1.5026,
    category: "nature",
    type: "veteran tree",
    description: "A substantial pedunculate oak stands at the corner of a field near Buckland, marked on old estate maps as a parish boundary tree — these were the fixed points from which boundaries were beaten and measured during the annual Rogationtide perambulation. This tree is old enough to have been a boundary marker in the Tudor period. Its girth and branching structure indicate an age of 400-500 years. It stands alone in a hedgerow with no companion trees of similar age nearby.",
    whyCurious: "The tree has been an administrative object for as long as it has been a tree. It was used as a legal marker before anyone currently alive was born. It continues to stand at the boundary corner regardless.",
