    name: "The Golden Farmer Pub Site, Shrivenham",
    lat: 51.6048,
    lng: -1.6534,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "highwayman history",
    description: "William Davies, known as the Golden Farmer, was a 17th century highwayman who conducted his criminal career from a legitimate farming base in this area of the Vale. He was so called because he always paid his bills in gold coin — the source of which his neighbours apparently did not question for years. He was eventually caught and hanged at Tyburn in 1690. The pub that took his name was a local landmark for centuries. The story is now almost entirely forgotten locally.",
