    name: "The Lapwing Winter Roost at Stanford Meadows",
    lat: 51.6391,
    lng: -1.5023,
    category: "nature",
    type: "wildlife watching",
    description: "The flood meadows between Stanford in the Vale and the Ock attract large flocks of lapwing from October through February — sometimes several thousand birds roosting on the flooded grassland overnight and feeding through the day. Golden plover join them in cold spells. At dusk the flocks come in from the surrounding arable land in skeins, the lapwing's distinctive rounded wings and tumbling flight creating patterns against the sky. The sound of a large lapwing flock calling is one of the most evocative sounds in the winter Vale.",
    whyCurious: "Lapwing are in serious decline nationally. The Vale flood meadows provide the winter habitat they need in numbers that are increasingly rare. In a good year this is one of the better lapwing sites in Oxfordshire.",
