    lat: 51.5383,
    lng: -1.6016,
    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "Iron Age hillfort",
    description: "Alfred's Castle is a small circular earthwork on the Downs above Ashdown — it is Iron Age, not Saxon, and the Alfred connection is entirely legendary, but the earthwork itself is well preserved and dramatically positioned. Excavations in the early 2000s revealed Iron Age occupation deposits and later Saxon reuse of the site. The rampart survives to over two metres in places. It sits in a copse of trees that makes it atmospheric in all seasons — beech trees whose roots disturb but also protect the ancient earthwork.",
