    category: "strange-or-historic",
    type: "village history",
    description: "The tiny hamlet of Noke, on the edge of Otmoor, was one of the communities that historically resisted drainage of the moor because local commoners depended on the wetland for wildfowling, fishing, and reed cutting. When Parliamentary enclosure came in 1815, Noke villagers rioted and pulled up the drainage ditches.",
