    description: "Farmoor Reservoir is Thames Water's largest reservoir in the upper Thames valley and one of Oxfordshire's best-kept birding secrets. The two basins hold nationally important numbers of wintering wildfowl, and the causeway between them is a prime seabird watching spot during autumn storms.",
    whyCurious: "Landlocked Oxfordshire is not where you expect to see Sabine's gulls, skuas, or storm petrels — but Farmoor delivers rare seabirds almost every autumn when Atlantic storms push oceanic birds inland. The reservoir also hosts England's most reliable breeding colony of common tern on the rafts, visible from the path.",
    cost: "Free",
    bestFor: "birdwatchers, especially in autumn and winter",
