    description: "Godstow Lock sits beside the ruined walls of Godstow Nunnery, founded in 1133. The nunnery is famous as the burial place of Fair Rosamund — Rosamund Clifford — King Henry II's mistress, whose tomb attracted pilgrims until the Bishop of Lincoln had her remains removed in 1191.",
    whyCurious: "Fair Rosamund's story generated an entire mythology: the legend of the bower at Woodstock where Henry hid her, the poisoning by Eleanor of Aquitaine, and the miraculous rose. None of it is reliably true, but Godstow Nunnery became a medieval pilgrimage site regardless. The ruins now stand in a meadow next to a busy lock, completely unbothered by their own drama.",
