    type: "common land",
    description: "Port Meadow is one of the most ancient unenclosed commons in England. The freemen of Oxford have grazed animals here since before the Norman Conquest — it is listed in the Domesday Book. Over 300 acres of flood-plain are never ploughed or treated with fertiliser, supporting remarkable wildflower and wading-bird populations.",
    whyCurious: "Port Meadow has never been ploughed in recorded history, making it one of the few places in England where you walk on the same surface as people in the Bronze Age. Its undisturbed flood-plain archaeology is extraordinary — ring ditches and field systems are visible from the air. In winter floods it becomes a vast lake used by thousands of wildfowl.",
