    category: "nature",
    type: "river gorge through chalk hills",
    description: "At Goring and Streatley the Thames cuts through the Chilterns-Berkshire Downs chalk ridge through a natural gap that is the only break in the chalk escarpment between East Anglia and Dorset. The river narrows, quickens, and the landscape changes dramatically from flat clay vale to wooded chalk valley.",
    whyCurious: "The Goring Gap is geologically ancient — the Thames established this course through the chalk during the Pleistocene when glacial meltwater forced it south. The gap is used by enormous numbers of migrating birds following the river corridor, making it a nationally important migration watch point in spring and autumn.",
