    description: "The old mill buildings at Goring weir have been converted to residential use but retain their Victorian industrial character. The mill was one of the last water-powered mills on the Thames, and the millrace still flows beneath the converted buildings. The setting beside the weir and lock is exceptional.",
    whyCurious: "The mill at Goring was featured by multiple Victorian painters, including Wilfrid Ball, as the definitive image of the working Thames. The millrace — the channel feeding water to the mill wheel — still flows at a significant speed through the buildings, audible from inside. The conversion preserved the structure while entirely changing its use.",
