    description: "Kelmscott Manor was the country home of William Morris from 1871 until his death in 1896. The sixteenth-century Cotswold stone manor stands a short walk from the Thames and contains furnishings, textiles, and designs by Morris and his Pre-Raphaelite circle. The manor is open to visitors.",
    whyCurious: "Morris arrived at Kelmscott by boat from London with Dante Gabriel Rossetti, punting up the Thames in 1871. The manor became the physical embodiment of his ideas about honest craft and simple beauty. His grave in the churchyard at Kelmscott is marked by a simple stone designed by Philip Webb — a monument to understatement by a man who decorated everything.",
