    description: "The Oxford Canal joins the Thames at Isis Lock near Jericho in Oxford, bringing the narrow boat route from Coventry and the Midlands waterways network. The junction was a major commercial hub in the early nineteenth century, when the canal was the primary route for coal into Oxford.",
    whyCurious: "The Oxford Canal was opened in 1790 and immediately transformed Oxford's economy by bringing cheap Warwickshire coal into the city. The canal wharf at Jericho became the industrial heart of Oxford, a role entirely forgotten in a city now defined by academic identity. The canal is now exclusively recreational and is one of England's most popular leisure waterways.",
