    description: "Cumnor Hill above the Thames valley was the backdrop for Matthew Arnold's Oxford poetry — Thyrsis, The Scholar Gypsy, and others. The Scholar Gypsy wanders these fields and crosses the Thames at Bablock Hythe. The hill is now largely suburban but the view west to the Thames valley is still recognisable.",
    whyCurious: "Arnold used the landscape visible from his study at Oxford — Cumnor Hill, Bablock Hythe, the Berkshire Downs — as the setting for his most sustained poetic meditation on lost youth and the death of idealism. The Scholar Gypsy has never died and never will — the poem's logic demands immortality as the price of avoiding the modern world.",
