    whyCurious: "The fort at Wittenham Clumps controlled what was then the major Thames crossing into the Midlands — the river was the boundary between tribal territories and crossing it was a political act requiring the permission of whoever held these hills. The beech trees on top were planted in the eighteenth century by a local landowner; the fort they stand in is 2,500 years older.",
