    whyCurious: "Dorchester was sufficiently important in the Roman period to control the lower Thames crossing for the entire region. The alignment of the Roman road through the village is still the main street. The town was then reused as an early Christian episcopal centre, making it one of the longest continuously occupied central places in the Thames valley.",
