    description: "The Goring Gap is a nationally significant migration bottle-neck for birds following the Thames valley corridor north and south between winter quarters and breeding grounds. Watching from the hills above Goring in April or October can reveal spectacular movements of hirundines, raptors, and finches.",
    whyCurious: "The Thames valley acts as a migration corridor funnelled through the only break in the chalk ridge between East Anglia and Dorset. Birds following the river hit the Goring Gap and are concentrated through this single point, creating passage densities far higher than elsewhere in the valley. On a good autumn day, thousands of swallows can pass in an hour.",
