    description: "The Thames at Streatley, in the Goring Gap where the river cuts through chalk hills, offers some of the best wild swimming on the upper river. The chalk geology keeps the water clear, the current through the gap quickens the flow, and the wooded banks provide shade. The Bull at Streatley overlooks the bridge and the swimming reach.",
    whyCurious: "Swimming in the Goring Gap, where the river has been cutting through chalk since the Pleistocene, is swimming in a genuinely ancient landscape feature. The water temperature is noticeably cooler here than on the clay vale reaches upstream, because it is draining off chalk rather than clay, and the clarity is remarkable. This reach inspired Richard Jefferies and has been painted by dozens of Victorian artists.",
